10:00.233 --> 10:04.571 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, first, he would help lead
efforts to
carry out one of Mr. Trump's
signature campaign

10:04.604 --> 10:09.075 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
pledges: repeal and replace the
Affordable
Care Act, also known as
Obamacare.

10:09.108 --> 10:10.443 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For more, we turn to Sarah
Kliff.

10:10.477 --> 10:12.979 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She has written extensively on
the topic for
the Web site Vox.

10:13.012 --> 10:16.182 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
What do we know about
Congressman Price and
the plans that he has already
had in mind?

10:16.216 --> 10:19.619 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SARAH KLIFF, Vox: So, he's a
congressman who
has spent a lot of time thinking
about repeal

10:19.652 --> 10:21.521 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and replace of Obamacare.

10:21.554 --> 10:26.593 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's the author of a 242-page
replacement
plan for Obamacare.

10:26.626 --> 10:30.597 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's the guy you would pick if
you're quite
serious about moving forward on
Obamacare

10:30.630 --> 10:32.165 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
repeal.

10:32.198 --> 10:34.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Republicans
have tried to
do repeal and replace before.

10:34.167 --> 10:35.368 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Even Speaker Ryan has a plan.

10:35.401 --> 10:37.070 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What do these plans have in
common?

10:37.103 --> 10:40.073 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SARAH KLIFF: So, they generally
cover fewer
people than Obamacare.

10:40.106 --> 10:42.308 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They would leave a few million
people uninsured.

10:42.342 --> 10:44.577 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The exact number depends on the
plan.

10:44.611 --> 10:48.615 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They're generally better for
young, healthy
people and worse for sick, older
people.

10:48.648 --> 10:50.383 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: How so?

10:50.416 --> 10:53.119 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SARAH KLIFF: They have a lot
less protections
for people with preexisting
conditions.

10:53.152 --> 10:57.590 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They make it possible for
insurance companies
to charge more to those who are
sick.

10:57.624 --> 11:00.960 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That would be a really big
change from Obamacare,
which outlaws those provisions.

11:00.994 --> 11:05.298 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And then what
does the pick
say of Seema Verma, who is going
to run Medicare

11:05.331 --> 11:08.902 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and Medicaid, say about this new
team that
he's putting in place?

11:08.935 --> 11:12.171 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
She's worked on Medicaid
expansion as a consultant
for different states?

11:12.205 --> 11:14.974 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SARAH KLIFF: She's incredibly
experienced
in Medicaid policy.

11:15.008 --> 11:18.811 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It suggests to me that the Trump
administration
is thinking about making some
big changes

11:18.845 --> 11:23.383 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to Medicaid, possibly adding
premiums into
the program, which serves
low-income Americans.

11:23.416 --> 11:27.921 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And is there
-- when we
talk about the changes that
could affect millions

11:27.954 --> 11:31.291 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of people -- we know Obamacare
gets this big
umbrella thing, but really on
brass tacks

11:31.324 --> 11:37.196 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
when it comes to specific
policies that impact
folks, so let's, for example,
take contraception

11:37.230 --> 11:38.197 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
coverage.

11:38.231 --> 11:40.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
How could that change?

11:40.066 --> 11:42.335 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SARAH KLIFF: That's something
that's very
easy for a Trump administration,
for Congressman

11:42.368 --> 11:45.271 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Price in office to really turn
back on day
one.

11:45.305 --> 11:48.675 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's something that the Obama
administration
did in regulations.

11:48.708 --> 11:50.410 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's not in the law.

11:50.443 --> 11:53.780 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
They could rewrite those
regulations to say
that contraceptives are no
longer covered

11:53.813 --> 11:55.582 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
under Obamacare.

11:55.615 --> 11:59.118 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And the
congressman is against
abortion, Congressman Price is,
right?

11:59.152 --> 12:03.990 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it takes something else to
try to get
even your personal view put into
legislation

12:04.023 --> 12:05.792 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that gets passed by all of
Congress.

12:05.825 --> 12:07.694 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
SARAH KLIFF: Sure.

12:07.727 --> 12:10.363 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is going to be a lot of
back-and-forth,
a lot of heated battles just
like we had around

12:10.396 --> 12:12.198 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Obamacare in 2010.

12:12.231 --> 12:17.637 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
There will be a lot of
infighting and figuring
out what does the Republican
agenda on health

12:17.670 --> 12:19.606 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
care look like?

12:19.639 --> 12:23.543 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What is one that Trump and
senators and Representative
Price at HHS now, what can they
agree on?

12:23.576 --> 12:24.944 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: What about
Medicare?

12:24.978 --> 12:27.347 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That affects a huge population
also covered
under this.

12:27.380 --> 12:29.983 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SARAH KLIFF: The Republicans
have a pretty
cohesive view for Medicare.

12:30.016 --> 12:34.020 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They want to switch it to more
of a voucher
program, where seniors get a set
amount of

12:34.053 --> 12:36.189 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
money, they shop for different
plans.

12:36.222 --> 12:38.157 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One of those plans might be a
government-run
Medicaid.

12:38.191 --> 12:42.128 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There would also be private
competitors and
they would kind of be using
their set amount

12:42.161 --> 12:44.364 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of money to pick whatever plan
they could
afford.

12:44.397 --> 12:47.467 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And how about
the health
-- I guess the health insurance
that most

12:47.500 --> 12:49.168 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of us get through employer
coverage?

12:49.202 --> 12:52.839 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SARAH KLIFF: There is a big
change to that
in Representative Price's plan
as well.

12:52.872 --> 12:58.144 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He would cap the tax exclusion
we right now
for insurance, meaning that the
cost of insurance

12:58.177 --> 13:02.415 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that you get at work, that could
go up pretty
significantly under
Representative Price's

13:02.448 --> 13:03.950 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
plan.

13:03.983 --> 13:05.985 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And so all of
these of course
have political consequences.

13:06.019 --> 13:09.122 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
When you feel it in your
personal pocketbook,
you might choose to vote a
different way.

13:09.155 --> 13:10.890 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
SARAH KLIFF: Yes.

13:10.923 --> 13:13.960 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think there will be things
that Republican
legislators like, that they like
in policy

13:13.993 --> 13:17.463 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and in theory, that are quite
politically
difficult to implement.

13:17.497 --> 13:21.801 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The cap on employer-sponsored
insurance is
a great example of that.

13:21.834 --> 13:25.905 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Democrats wanted to make the
same change in
2010, but they found it was
politically impossible

13:25.938 --> 13:26.973 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to do so.

13:27.006 --> 13:28.708 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I think Republicans will face
similar barriers.

13:28.741 --> 13:31.277 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
Sarah Kliff from
Vox, thanks so much.

13:31.310 --> 13:33.279 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
SARAH KLIFF: Thank you.

13:33.312 --> 13:35.615 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
let's dig a little
deeper now on the potential
fallout for Obamacare

13:35.648 --> 13:37.483 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and the people who use its
benefits.

13:37.517 --> 13:41.921 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Sabrina Corlette specializes in
health insurance
markets, as a research professor
at Georgetown

13:41.954 --> 13:43.856 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
University.

13:43.890 --> 13:46.359 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And Bob Moffit is a senior
fellow at the Heritage
Foundation's center for Health
Policy Studies.

13:46.392 --> 13:49.729 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Trump team has been meeting
with people
at Heritage Foundation during
this transition.

13:49.762 --> 13:51.964 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, Bob Moffit, what does this
appointment
signal to you?

13:51.998 --> 13:55.868 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ROBERT MOFFIT, Heritage
Foundation: It signals
that president-elect Trump is
very serious

13:55.902 --> 14:00.339 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
about the promise to repeal and
replace Obamacare.

14:00.373 --> 14:07.246 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The appointment of Congressman
Price is the
appointment of an individual who
has a long

14:07.280 --> 14:12.685 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
experience in health policy in
the House and
has introduced legislation to
repeal Obamacare

14:12.719 --> 14:15.688 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and to replace it with
provisions of his own.

14:15.722 --> 14:19.726 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So I think from the standpoint
of the administration,
this is a very serious
appointment.

14:19.759 --> 14:25.998 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's a very, very big signal to
both the House
and the Senate that the Trump
administration

14:26.032 --> 14:27.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is very serious about this
issue.

14:27.834 --> 14:32.638 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Sabrina
Corlette, he has
had a 240-plus page plan already
on the books.

14:32.672 --> 14:35.908 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's in addition to all the
other Republican
plans that are out there to
repeal and replace.

14:35.942 --> 14:37.710 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SABRINA CORLETTE, Center on
Health Insurance
Reforms, Georgetown University:
Right.

14:37.744 --> 14:42.115 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think one thing that Mr.
Moffit and I would
absolutely agree on is that the
nomination

14:42.148 --> 14:49.021 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of Mr. Price is a clear signal
that the repeal
of Obamacare is a top priority
for this new

14:49.055 --> 14:50.957 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
president.

14:50.990 --> 14:56.295 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
However, I don't think that we
can say anything
that the Republicans have put
forward, including

14:56.329 --> 15:02.301 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Mr. Price, constitutes a
replacement of the
Affordable Care Act, because
none of the proposals,

15:02.335 --> 15:07.640 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
including Mr. Price's proposal,
would cover
nearly the same number of people
that the

15:07.673 --> 15:12.011 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Affordable Care Act covers, nor
would it provide
the same consumer protections
for people with

15:12.044 --> 15:13.446 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
preexisting conditions.

15:13.479 --> 15:16.382 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Now, Robert
Moffit, again,
a plan does not exist.

15:16.415 --> 15:19.952 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We're talking about based on
what he's proposed
before and what other
Republicans have proposed

15:19.986 --> 15:20.953 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
before.

15:20.987 --> 15:22.822 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ROBERT MOFFIT: Right.

15:22.855 --> 15:25.258 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: What's the
cost that maybe
the new administration is
willing to tolerate

15:25.291 --> 15:27.226 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in the number of people that
got...

15:27.260 --> 15:31.230 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT MOFFIT: Well, I think
that the president-elect
himself made a comment at the
very beginning

15:31.264 --> 15:36.669 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of this, and actually put it in
print, that,
in fact, nobody should fall
through the cracks.

15:36.702 --> 15:42.308 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Remember that Tom Price is an
orthopedic surgeon,
so I think what we're looking at
is a surgical

15:42.341 --> 15:45.545 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
approach to the Affordable Care
Act.

15:45.578 --> 15:48.981 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I don't think what you will see
is any kind
of massive disruption.

15:49.015 --> 15:53.686 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think the major concern right
now for those
of us in health policy is that
we are already

15:53.719 --> 15:59.358 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
facing a massive instability in
the insurance
markets, particularly in the
small group and

15:59.392 --> 16:01.160 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the individual markets.

16:01.194 --> 16:07.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
With premiums jumping 25 percent
nationwide,
average premiums in the
exchanges, and then

16:07.433 --> 16:12.338 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
with these breathtaking
deductibles -- for
a family with a bronze plan,
you're talking

16:12.371 --> 16:18.144 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about a $12,000 deductible --
health insurance
is becoming less and less
affordable for millions

16:18.177 --> 16:19.979 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of Americans.

16:20.012 --> 16:24.217 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The people in the exchanges is
only one part
of this problem -- or only one
part of this

16:24.250 --> 16:26.185 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
problem.

16:26.219 --> 16:29.822 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But you got about 10 million
people in the
individual market outside of the
exchanges

16:29.856 --> 16:34.660 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who do not get any subsidies at
all who are
being affected by this, and then
you also

16:34.694 --> 16:39.765 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have another 15 million people
in the group
market, so -- small group
market.

16:39.799 --> 16:45.471 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So this problem that we have
right now with
affordability and cost and the
instability

16:45.504 --> 16:48.975 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of the insurance market is
affecting millions
of people.

16:49.008 --> 16:53.646 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What that means is, is that the
administration
cannot waste time on this.

16:53.679 --> 16:57.516 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They have to come to the rescue
of people
to make sure that those who have
coverage

16:57.550 --> 17:01.554 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
don't actually lose it, and we
have higher
rates of uninsurance as a result
of it.

17:01.587 --> 17:05.358 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Sabrina
Corlette, how do
you take a surgical approach,
but also contain

17:05.391 --> 17:07.126 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
costs?

17:07.159 --> 17:10.196 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SABRINA CORLETTE: Well, I'm not
sure how you
take a surgical approach, based
on what we

17:10.229 --> 17:14.700 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have heard Mr. Price and other
congressional
leaders, as well as the
president-elect, say.

17:14.734 --> 17:18.738 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They have called for a wholesale
repeal of
the Affordable Care Act.

17:18.771 --> 17:22.575 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That would include expansion of
Medicaid,
which is the program that covers
low-income

17:22.608 --> 17:24.443 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
people.

17:24.477 --> 17:29.615 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That would include a repeal of
the tax credits
that help moderate-income people
afford coverage,

17:29.649 --> 17:33.085 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
as well as the individual
mandate, which is
supposed to get healthy people
into the pool

17:33.119 --> 17:35.922 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
and make coverage more
affordable across the
board.

17:35.955 --> 17:42.328 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Once you repeal all of that,
that's going
to cause massive disruption in
the market.

17:42.361 --> 17:46.265 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, that's going to throw as
many as 22 million
people off of coverage.

17:46.299 --> 17:49.568 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Now, Mr. Price has put forward a
bill.

17:49.602 --> 17:56.075 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
However, the tax credits that it
provides
are a tiny fraction of what the
Affordable

17:56.108 --> 17:57.910 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Care Act provides to people.

17:57.944 --> 18:02.982 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They're also not income-based,
so they heavily
favor higher-income people over
lower-income

18:03.015 --> 18:04.817 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
people.

18:04.850 --> 18:08.387 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And then if you have a
preexisting condition
and you have even a tiny lapse
in coverage,

18:08.421 --> 18:10.189 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
you're left out in the cold.

18:10.222 --> 18:12.525 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Mr. Moffit,
this is also
on the heels of president-elect
Trump coming

18:12.558 --> 18:17.563 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
out and saying, listen, he'd
like to preserve
the clause that says you can't
discriminate

18:17.596 --> 18:18.798 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
on preexisting conditions.

18:18.831 --> 18:19.799 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's almost universally
agreed.

18:19.832 --> 18:21.667 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
There is nobody that wants that.

18:21.701 --> 18:24.670 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT MOFFIT: There is nobody
who is arguing
that we should exclude
individuals from health

18:24.704 --> 18:28.174 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
insurance coverage because they
are sick or
they have a preexisting
condition.

18:28.207 --> 18:29.408 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
That's nonsense.

18:29.442 --> 18:30.509 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's never been the debate.

18:30.543 --> 18:32.345 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The question is, what is the
best way to do
it?

18:32.378 --> 18:34.146 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And how do you
pay for that?

18:34.180 --> 18:35.948 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT MOFFIT: Well, you're
going to have
to pay for it in any event,
because we're

18:35.982 --> 18:37.817 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
paying for it one way or
another.

18:37.850 --> 18:41.487 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If people do not get access to
health insurance
and they end up in the hospital
emergency

18:41.520 --> 18:45.624 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
room, the most expensive place
on the planet,
tax players are stuck with the
bill.

18:45.658 --> 18:47.493 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, we have got to address this.

18:47.526 --> 18:52.732 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Frankly, I think that a
mainstream proposal
right now that is circulating
among House

18:52.765 --> 18:58.371 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Republicans is to adopt one of
the practices
that we have in group insurance
right now

18:58.404 --> 19:02.641 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
under the Health Insurance
Affordability and
Accountability Act, which is
this, is that

19:02.675 --> 19:07.680 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
if you have credible coverage,
creditable
coverage, and you move from one
job to another

19:07.713 --> 19:13.386 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and join different types of
groups, you cannot
be rated up, regardless of any
kind of preexisting

19:13.419 --> 19:14.387 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
condition.

19:14.420 --> 19:16.322 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Yes.

19:16.355 --> 19:18.891 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT MOFFIT: We do not have
any kind of
crisis of preexisting conditions
in employment-based

19:18.924 --> 19:19.892 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
health insurance.

19:19.925 --> 19:22.061 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The problem is in the individual
market.

19:22.094 --> 19:26.465 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you're going to be personally
responsible
and buy insurance at an
affordable rate, you

19:26.499 --> 19:27.466 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
can do that.

19:27.500 --> 19:29.602 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Otherwise, you can be rated up.

19:29.635 --> 19:34.340 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That puts the responsibility
where it belongs,
on the individual who is buying
the insurance.

19:34.373 --> 19:39.912 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SABRINA CORLETTE: Well, for
people who have
come off an employer-based plan,
that typically

19:39.945 --> 19:42.848 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
